<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Grounds decision <a href="/backlog/584-general-reference-retirement-convention-generalize-the-corpu/">#584</a>:
  <a href="/backlog/546-corpus-source-fast-has-a-dead-docsurl-fast-docs-decommission/">#546</a> marked the
  benchmark corpus's first dead source with a <code>retired</code> shape
  (<code>retired</code>/<code>retiredDate</code>/<code>retiredReason</code>, keep-not-delete). The same death —
  and the subtler <em>moved</em>, <em>superseded</em>, and <em>content-drift</em> failure modes — can hit any
  external URL the project cites, and those citations live in <strong>heterogeneous homes</strong>. #584 asks
  what one convention governs all of them, where it lives, and how it meshes with
  <a href="/backlog/192-longitudinal-research-freshness-system/">#192</a>'s existing
  <code>supersedes</code>/<code>supersededBy</code> chain. This is the
  <a href="/backlog/583-external-reference-health-monitoring-liveness-retirement-rep/">#583</a> epic's
  <strong>dogfood layer</strong> — a self-run convention over this repo, not the later WE platform setting.
</p>

<h2>Where the project cites external references</h2>
<p>
  An inventory of the tree finds two clusters. <strong>Structured JSON homes with external URLs</strong> are the
  convention's real target: corpus sources (<code>benchmarkCorpus.json</code> — <code>docsUrl</code>/<code>repoUrl</code>,
  the only home that already has <code>retired</code>), library references (<code>references.json</code>),
  block &amp; intent design-system refs (<code>designSystemResearch[].reference</code> in
  <code>blocks.json</code>/<code>intents.json</code>), and deep per-row doc URLs
  (<code>benchmarkCapabilityPresence.json</code>). <strong>Freeform prose homes</strong> — dated
  <code>reports/*.md</code> and the <code>research-descriptions/*.njk</code> partials — cite inline markdown
  links no field-set can enforce. <a href="/research/">Research topics</a> already carry the <em>replacement</em>
  half of the model (<code>supersededBy</code> + <code>lastReviewed</code>/<code>reviewHorizon</code> from
  #192/#441/#477/#478); backlog <code>crossRef</code> cites only internal links; adapters/protocols cite no
  external URLs yet. Validation today is one rule — a warning when a <code>verified</code> presence row lacks a
  <code>url</code> — and there are no JSON Schema files; validation is imperative in
  <code>check-standards-rules.mjs</code>.
</p>

<h2>What the prior-art survey found</h2>
<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>The retirement vocabulary is document-type-agnostic.</strong>
    <a href="https://www.w3.org/guide/process/obsolete-rescinded-supserseded.html">W3C</a> applies the
    <em>same</em> lifecycle states to a Recommendation, a Note, and a Group decision; IETF applies the same
    headers to every RFC regardless of stream. The homes differ in <em>container</em>, not in the retirement
    <em>concept</em> — the strongest argument for one uniform shape over per-home shapes.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Death and supersession are distinct, linkable states — not one axis.</strong> W3C separates
    <strong>superseded</strong> (a newer version is recommended, but the old stays <em>valid</em>) from
    <strong>obsolete</strong> (no longer used) and <strong>rescinded</strong> (withdrawn). IETF mirrors this
    with bidirectional <code>Obsoletes:</code>/<code>Updates:</code> headers (replacement) <em>plus a separate</em>
    <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7805.html">Historic status</a> (no longer current). Python PEP
    (<code>Superseded-By:</code>) and ADR (<code>Supersedes</code>/<code>SupersededBy</code>) carry only the
    replacement pointer.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>The minimal marker is a keep-not-delete boolean.</strong>
    <a href="https://www.learnjsonschema.com/2020-12/meta-data/deprecated/">JSON Schema / OpenAPI</a> use a
    single <code>deprecated: true</code> annotation: advisory, no behavioural change, the entry stays in place —
    exactly #546's <code>retired</code> instinct.
  </li>
</ol>

<h2>How this reshapes the decision</h2>
<p>
  Finding&nbsp;2 dissolves the original "how does it interact with #192's supersedes chain?" fork into a concrete
  choice: model death and replacement as <strong>two orthogonal markers</strong> (a <code>retired</code> boolean
  triplet for death, reusing #192's <code>supersededBy</code> pointer for replacement — a reference can be both,
  as FAST is) versus folding them into <strong>one richer W3C-style <code>status</code> enum</strong>
  (<code>active</code>/<code>superseded</code>/<code>obsolete</code>/<code>rescinded</code>). The orthogonal-marker
  path wins under the standing
  <a href="/backlog/">bias toward separation</a> and most-permissive-default biases: it reuses shipped vocabulary
  (#546 + #192), needs no enum migration, and keeps the markers composable.
</p>

<h2>Classification — data governance, not a standards artifact</h2>
<p>
  Like #546, #584 governs the project's <em>internal reference data</em>, not a project-facing WE standard (that
  is #583's later layer-2 platform setting). The Block/Intent/Protocol/Capability layer sequence is N/A. The
  binding principles are native-first vocabulary reuse (borrow <code>retired</code>/<code>supersededBy</code>/<code>deprecated</code>,
  don't mint jargon), reproducibility under #192 (keep-not-delete so a re-run sees <em>why</em> a reference left),
  bias-toward-separation (orthogonal markers over a fused enum), and most-permissive default (the metadata is
  opt-in, never a required field).
</p>

<h2>The four forks, at a glance</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Uniform shape</strong> applied to every structured JSON home (vs per-home shapes).</li>
  <li><strong>One documented convention + one shared validator helper</strong> in
    <code>check-standards-rules.mjs</code> (vs duplicated per-home definitions).</li>
  <li><strong>Two orthogonal markers</strong> reusing #192's <code>supersededBy</code> (vs a single
    <code>status</code> enum).</li>
  <li><strong>Structured homes now</strong>; freeform prose gets a documented style only, structured extraction
    deferred to <a href="/backlog/597-reference-registry-substrate-index-the-structured-reference-/">#597</a>.</li>
</ul>
